{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570173"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:39:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:39:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660243"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:21:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22768"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.04,0.05,0.84,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94134"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"5093"},{"type":"tags","id":"8743"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45907"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45908"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of a burning sensation in her tongue and altered taste. She has not had oral ulcers, odynophagia, or weight loss. Her medical history includes gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications are esomeprazole and metformin. Four months ago, she had a chest infection that was treated with antibiotics. She follows a vegetarian diet, does not drink alcohol, and does not smoke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her tongue is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Candidiasis","Amyloidosis","Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis","Vitamin B12 deficiency","Epstein\u2013Barr virus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe appearances of a smooth, erythematous, depapillated tongue are consistent with atrophic glossitis. This can arise from nutritional deficiencies, infection, autoimmune disease, or irritants. In primary care, synthesising history, examination, and basic blood tests helps differentiate causes. Risk factors that impair vitamin B12 absorption include vegetarian diets, long-term acid suppression, and use of metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECandidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with removable white curd-like plaques or erythematous patches with burning after antibiotics or inhaled steroids. The absence of removable plaques makes this less likely. Whilst her course of antibiotics for the chest infection may have been complicated by candidiasis, this would not explain the current appearance of her tongue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyloidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can involve the tongue, causing macroglossia with indentations from teeth along the lateral borders. However, the tongue typically appears enlarged and firm rather than smooth and depapillated. Systemic features such as cardiac or renal involvement would be expected, and the isolated glossitis presentation makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmyotrophic lateral sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a progressive neurodegenerative disorder affecting motor neurons. While it can cause bulbar symptoms including tongue fasciculations and atrophy, it does not cause the smooth, erythematous, depapillated appearance of glossitis. The absence of other motor neuron signs such as muscle weakness, fasciculations, or hyperreflexia makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin B12 deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is most consistent with the presentation: a vegetarian diet reduces intake; proton pump inhibitor therapy reduces gastric acid needed to release protein-bound vitamin B12; metformin impairs ileal uptake of the vitamin B12\u2013intrinsic factor complex. The smooth, burning tongue with depapillation is characteristic of B12 deficiency glossitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein\u2013Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E usually causes a pharyngitis-like illness with fever, lymphadenopathy, and fatigue. It does not cause isolated chronic glossitis. It could cause a leukoplakia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glossitis with a smooth, burning tongue should prompt evaluation for vitamin B12 deficiency, especially with metformin use, vegetarian diet, and acid suppression.","Metformin and proton pump inhibitors reduce vitamin B12 absorption through effects on intrinsic factor\u2013B12 uptake and gastric acid\u2013dependent release.","Distinguishing nutritional glossitis from candidiasis relies on absence of removable white plaques and presence of systemic features like pallor and paraesthesiae."],"references":["Straub L, Schettini P, Mire P. Common Tongue Conditions in Primary Care. Am Fam Physician. 2024; 110:467-75. Available from: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2010/0301/p627.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94134"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22768"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22068"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22068"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/j9p3IzvefojljWN1orsQknH82rw0Ob.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/j9p3IzvefojljWN1orsQknH82rw0Ob.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":375,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94134"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-24T17:27:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-24T17:27:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id"